<task id="083" project="spaarke-ai-platform-unification-r6">
  <metadata>
    <title>D-D-04 References Resolver — `#scope`, `@&lt;entity&gt;`, `#&lt;filename&gt;` resolved at parse time</title>
    <phase>Phase D — Command Router + Integration + Closeout</phase>
    <status>completed</status>
    <estimated-effort>7 hours</estimated-effort>
    <dependencies>080</dependencies>
    <blocks>084</blocks>
    <tags>frontend, typescript, ai-widgets, command-router</tags>
    <rigor-hint>FULL</rigor-hint>
    <rigor-reason>References resolve to context the agent uses; touches scope library + session file index + workspace tab registry; spec FR-51 binding; Phase D exit criterion 4 binding.</rigor-reason>
    <parallel-group>D-G1</parallel-group>
    <parallel-safe>true</parallel-safe>
    <parallel-reason>ReferenceResolver lives in its own file; works alongside HardSlashExecutor (081) and SoftSlashRouter (082) without file overlap.</parallel-reason>
  </metadata>

  <prompt>
    Build the references resolver per spec FR-51 — resolves `#scope`, `@&lt;entity&gt;`, and
    `#&lt;filename&gt;` at PARSE TIME so the agent receives resolved entities in its prompt
    (no extra LLM round-trips for disambiguation).

    Per Q6 + FR-51 the 3 reference types are:
    - `#scope` → resolves to a scope library reference (uses existing `IScopeResolverService`
      via BFF endpoint `/api/ai/scopes/*`). Examples: `#summarize-action`, `#engagement-letter-skill`.
    - `@&lt;entity&gt;` → resolves to matter/person/organization (Dataverse polymorphic).
      Examples: `@matter`, `@opposing-counsel`, `@acme-corp`.
    - `#&lt;filename&gt;` → resolves to a session file (Pillar 4 session-files index) or open
      workspace tab. Examples: `#engagement-letter.docx`, `#motion-to-dismiss.pdf`.

    Build `ReferenceResolver.ts` that takes `Intent.references[]` (raw tokens) and returns
    `ResolvedReference[]` with each token expanded to: type + canonical ID + display name +
    metadata. Resolved references are added to the agent prompt as known entities
    (FR-51 acceptance: "resolved entities appear in agent prompt").

    Resolver caches resolutions per session (avoid re-resolving the same `@matter` repeatedly).
    Unresolved references degrade gracefully — pass the raw token to the agent with `resolved: false`
    flag so the agent can ask for clarification. NFR-01 binding: resolver never blocks the
    conversation.

    Frontend-only task; BFF publish-size delta = 0 MB.
  </prompt>

  <role>
    Senior frontend engineer with familiarity with Dataverse polymorphic resolution, scope library
    endpoints, and session-files / workspace-tab registries. Comfortable with caching strategies
    + graceful degradation for unresolved references.
  </role>

  <goal>
    `ReferenceResolver.ts` exists and resolves 3 reference types. Resolved references appear in
    the chat message payload so the agent prompt includes them as known entities. Caching
    prevents redundant resolution. Unresolved references degrade gracefully without breaking
    the conversation. Tests cover each reference type + caching + degraded path.
  </goal>

  <inputs>
    <file purpose="project-spec">projects/spaarke-ai-platform-unification-r6/spec.md</file>
    <file purpose="project-plan">projects/spaarke-ai-platform-unification-r6/plan.md</file>
    <file purpose="project-claude">projects/spaarke-ai-platform-unification-r6/CLAUDE.md</file>
